File_Description:
English Deltware group. From left to right: 

C.1423 & A-1928: Covered tankard. Probably made at the Pickleherring pottery in Southwark. Cylindrical with slightly recessed base and narrow footrim, and with a loop handle which is concave on the outside and has a rounded terminal at the lower end. The domed cover has a narrow rim, and a capstan-shaped knob. The front is painted in blue with a castellated gate tower with a portcullis, and a conical roof, flying a flag bearing the red cross of St George, with a yellow crown at the top of the pole above it. Below are the initials and date: C\T H\1660. Earthenware, the body thrown, tin-glazed overall, and painted in blue, yellow, and red high-temperature (metallic oxide) colours, height, whole, 26.9 cm, dated 1660. 

C.7-2001: Ewer. Probably made at the Pickleherring pottery in Southwark. Earthenware, thrown and manipulated, with applied vertically grooved handle, tin-glazed, and painted in blue; the edge of the foot has been wiped almost entirely free of glaze. height, whole, 24.0 cm, diameter, foot, 11.8 cm, width, whole, 19.5 cm, dated 1660. 

C.8-2001: Basin. Probably made at the Pickleherring pottery in Southwark. This basin was made for a couple whose surname began with C. Painted in blue with a circular cartouche, enclosing initials and date C/TH/1660 surrounded by ribbon, scrolling foliage and a winged cherub's head. Circular with deep everted sides with alternately wide and narrow lobes (eight of each). The base is flat with a circular depression (convex on the underside) round the centre. The area within the depression is decorated with a circular cartouche with a loop of ribbon at the top, scrolling foliage on each side, and a winged cherub's head at the bottom, enclosing the initials 'C/T H' over '1660'. Pale buff earthenware (little visible), tin-glazed and painted in blue, height, whole, 6.5 cm, diameter, whole, 39.6 cm, dated 1660. 

(last) C.6 & A-2001:  Covered tankard. Probably made at the Pickleherring pottery in Southwark. There are several 'pinholes' in the glaze on the interior and exterior. Cylindrical with a loop handle which has a vertical depression, and a slight, stumpy kick at the lower end. The circular cover has a narrow sloping rim, a domed centre, and a mushroom-shaped knob. Inside there is a circular flange which fits inside the tankard. The front of the tankard is decorated with a circular castellated tower with an arched doorway and portcullis, which has on its pointed roof, a flag pole topped by a crown and cross, flying a flag with the arms of London, a red cross on a white ground. Below the tower are the initials 'C/T . H' over '1660'. Pale buff earthenware, tin-glazed, painted in blue, and a little red, height, whole, 26.9 cm, diameter, cover, 13.1 cm, width, whole, 15.6 cm, dated 1660. Notes: It has a pair, C.1423 & A-1928. This tankard and cover were made for a couple whose surname began with C.
